{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_019yThHVXw1ZXTR4TbV3zugY","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect. I've read all three files completely. Here's a comprehensive summary of the route patterns, authentication, pagination, and database patterns in your codebase:\n\n## Summary\n\n### 1. Route Creation (Factory Pattern)\n\nAll routes follow a consistent **factory function pattern**:\n\n```typescript\nexport function createXxxRoutes(deps: XxxRoutesDeps) {\n  const { db } = deps;\n  const app = new Hono<AppEnv>();\n  \n  app.get(\"/path\", async (c) => { ... });\n  \n  return app;\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Each route file exports a factory function that accepts a `deps` object containing `db` (and sometimes other dependencies)\n- Creates a new `Hono<AppEnv>()` instance scoped to that route\n- Returns the app for registration via `app.route()` in `index.ts`\n- In `index.ts`, routes are mounted with: `app.route(\"/path\", createXxxRoutes({ db }))`\n\n### 2. JWT Authentication Pattern\n\nAuthentication is applied at the middleware level in `index.ts`, not per-route:\n\n```typescript\n// Applied before route registration\napp.use(\n  \"/challenges/*\",\n  createJwtAuthMiddleware({ jwtSecret: config.jwtSecret, requireAllMethods: true }),\n);\napp.route(\"/challenges\", createChallengeRoutes({ db }));\n```\n\n**Inside routes**, extract userId from context:\n```typescript\nconst userId = c.get(\"userId\");\nif (!userId) {\n  return c.json({ error: \"Authentication required\" }, 401);\n}\n```\n\nThe middleware stores `userId` in the Hono context (`c.get(\"userId\")`), making it available in route handlers.\n\n### 3. Pagination Pattern (Cursor-Based)\n\nPagination uses **cursor-based pagination** (not offset-based). Pattern from `points.ts`:\n\n```typescript\nconst cursor = c.req.query(\"cursor\") || undefined;\nconst limit = parseIntParam(c.req.query(\"limit\"), 20, 50);\n\n// Cursor filter: id < cursor for DESC ordering\nconst cursorFilter = cursor\n  ? db.rawSql`AND id < ${cursor}`\n  : db.rawSql``;\n\nconst rows = await db.rawSql<RowType[]>`\n  SELECT ...\n  FROM table\n  WHERE user_id = ${userId} ${cursorFilter}\n  ORDER BY id DESC\n  LIMIT ${limit}\n`;\n\n// Compute next cursor if we got a full page\nconst nextCursor =\n  items.length === limit ? String(items[items.length - 1]!.id) : null;\n\nreturn c.json({ items, nextCursor });\n```\n\n**Key details:**\n- `parseIntParam(raw, defaultVal, max)` — safely parses query params, returns default if missing/invalid, clamps to max\n- Cursor is the **last item's ID** from previous page\n- Filter: `id < cursor` (for DESC ordering, assumes monotonic IDs)\n- Response: `{ items: [...], nextCursor: string | null }` — `nextCursor` is null if page didn't fill (no more data)\n\n### 4. Database Query Pattern\n\nAll queries use **raw parameterized SQL** via template literals:\n\n```typescript\nconst rows = await db.rawSql<RowType[]>`\n  SELECT col1, col2\n  FROM table\n  WHERE user_id = ${userId}\n    AND status = ${status}\n  ORDER BY created_at DESC\n  LIMIT ${limit}\n`;\n```\n\n**Key conventions from the codebase:**\n- Generic type param: `db.rawSql<RowType[]>` — specifies return type\n- Template literals with `${}` placeholders — parameterized to prevent SQL injection\n- Column names in snake_case (database convention)\n- Timestamps returned as `Date` objects (auto-parsed)\n- Numeric columns (id, balance, count) returned as strings, then coerced with `Number()`\n- JSON columns (metadata) returned as `Record<string, unknown>`\n- JOIN queries common for enriched data (e.g., challenge_assignments JOIN challenges)\n\n**From challenges.ts — complex query example:**\n```typescript\nasync function getAssignmentsForPeriod(db: Db, userId: string, periodKey: string) {\n  return db.rawSql<AssignmentRow[]>`\n    SELECT\n      ca.id,\n      ca.challenge_id,\n      ca.period_key,\n      ca.status,\n      ca.progress,\n      ca.target,\n      ca.expires_at,\n      ca.completed_at,\n      c.title,\n      c.description,\n      c.reward_type,\n      c.reward_amount,\n      camp.campaign_type\n    FROM challenge_assignments ca\n    JOIN challenges c ON c.id = ca.challenge_id\n    JOIN campaigns camp ON camp.id = c.campaign_id\n    WHERE ca.user_id = ${userId}\n      AND ca.period_key = ${periodKey}\n    ORDER BY c.sort_order ASC\n  `;\n}\n```\n\n### 5. Type Patterns\n\nEach route file defines its DB dependency interface and row types:\n\n```typescript\nexport interface ChallengeRoutesDeps {\n  db: Db;\n}\n\ninterface AssignmentRow {\n  id: string;\n  challenge_id: string;\n  status: string;\n  progress: number;\n  target: number;\n  expires_at: string | null;\n  completed_at: string | null;\n  title: string;\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\n**Response formatting pattern:**\nConvert DB row types to camelCase for JSON response:\n```typescript\nconst formatChallenge = (a: AssignmentRow) => ({\n  id: Number(a.id),\n  title: a.title,\n  progress: a.progress,\n  status: a.status as \"active\" | \"completed\" | \"expired\",\n  completedAt: a.completed_at ?? null,\n});\n```\n\n### 6. Error Handling\n\nConsistent pattern across routes:\n```typescript\ntry {\n  // Query logic\n} catch (err) {\n  logger.error(\"context message\", {\n    userId,\n    error: err instanceof Error ? err.message : String(err),\n  });\n  return c.json({ error: \"User-friendly message\" }, 500);\n}\n```\n\n### 7. Route Registration Flow (from index.ts)\n\n1. **Middleware applied first** (JWT auth, rate limiting) at path prefix\n2. **Route factory called with deps** (db, config, etc.)\n3. **Route mounted** via `app.route()`\n\nExample:\n```typescript\n// 1. Apply JWT auth middleware\napp.use(\n  \"/challenges/*\",\n  createJwtAuthMiddleware({ jwtSecret: config.jwtSecret, requireAllMethods: true }),\n);\n\n// 2. Mount routes\napp.route(\"/challenges\", createChallengeRoutes({ db }));\n```\n\n---\n\n## For Your `/mine/history` Implementation\n\nBased on these patterns, your new challenges history endpoint should:\n\n1. **Inherit JWT auth** — add middleware to `/challenges/*` (already in place)\n2. **Use cursor pagination** — query from `challenge_assignments` with `cursor` and `limit` params\n3. **Return consistent shape** — `{ items: [...], nextCursor: string | null }`\n4. **Add to challenges.ts** as a new route: `app.get(\"/mine/history\", async (c) => {...})`\n5. **Type the row result** and format to camelCase for response\n6. **Handle userId extraction and auth checks** at route start\n\nThe existing `/mine` endpoint in challenges.ts is already there — you just need to add `/mine/history` as a sibling route in the same factory function."}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8b2f7dd7-97bd-434b-b775-f78d70040f2b","uuid":"254b57dd-97ed-431f-b8d8-c81613c13c50","timestamp":"2026-04-03T21:04:08.154Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"I need to understand the existing route patterns in this backend codebase to implement new endpoints. Please read these files and summarize:\n\n1. `/workspaces/rng-utopia/backend/services/backend/src/routes/challenges.ts` - the existing challenges route file (I need to add /mine/history here)\n2. `/workspaces/rng-utopia/backend/services/backend/src/routes/points.ts` - has pagination pattern I need to follow\n3. `/workspaces/rng-utopia/backend/services/backend/src/index.ts` - route registration\n\nFocus on:\n- How routes are created (factory pattern)\n- How pagination works (cursor-based?)\n- How JWT auth is applied\n- How DB queries are made\n- The exact types/interfaces used\n\nBe thorough - read each file completely.","agentId":"a4a4238f68c7f5b2a","agentType":"Explore","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect. I've read all three files completely. Here's a comprehensive summary of the route patterns, authentication, pagination, and database patterns in your codebase:\n\n## Summary\n\n### 1. Route Creation (Factory Pattern)\n\nAll routes follow a consistent **factory function pattern**:\n\n```typescript\nexport function createXxxRoutes(deps: XxxRoutesDeps) {\n  const { db } = deps;\n  const app = new Hono<AppEnv>();\n  \n  app.get(\"/path\", async (c) => { ... });\n  \n  return app;\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Each route file exports a factory function that accepts a `deps` object containing `db` (and sometimes other dependencies)\n- Creates a new `Hono<AppEnv>()` instance scoped to that route\n- Returns the app for registration via `app.route()` in `index.ts`\n- In `index.ts`, routes are mounted with: `app.route(\"/path\", createXxxRoutes({ db }))`\n\n### 2. JWT Authentication Pattern\n\nAuthentication is applied at the middleware level in `index.ts`, not per-route:\n\n```typescript\n// Applied before route registration\napp.use(\n  \"/challenges/*\",\n  createJwtAuthMiddleware({ jwtSecret: config.jwtSecret, requireAllMethods: true }),\n);\napp.route(\"/challenges\", createChallengeRoutes({ db }));\n```\n\n**Inside routes**, extract userId from context:\n```typescript\nconst userId = c.get(\"userId\");\nif (!userId) {\n  return c.json({ error: \"Authentication required\" }, 401);\n}\n```\n\nThe middleware stores `userId` in the Hono context (`c.get(\"userId\")`), making it available in route handlers.\n\n### 3. Pagination Pattern (Cursor-Based)\n\nPagination uses **cursor-based pagination** (not offset-based). Pattern from `points.ts`:\n\n```typescript\nconst cursor = c.req.query(\"cursor\") || undefined;\nconst limit = parseIntParam(c.req.query(\"limit\"), 20, 50);\n\n// Cursor filter: id < cursor for DESC ordering\nconst cursorFilter = cursor\n  ? db.rawSql`AND id < ${cursor}`\n  : db.rawSql``;\n\nconst rows = await db.rawSql<RowType[]>`\n  SELECT ...\n  FROM table\n  WHERE user_id = ${userId} ${cursorFilter}\n  ORDER BY id DESC\n  LIMIT ${limit}\n`;\n\n// Compute next cursor if we got a full page\nconst nextCursor =\n  items.length === limit ? String(items[items.length - 1]!.id) : null;\n\nreturn c.json({ items, nextCursor });\n```\n\n**Key details:**\n- `parseIntParam(raw, defaultVal, max)` — safely parses query params, returns default if missing/invalid, clamps to max\n- Cursor is the **last item's ID** from previous page\n- Filter: `id < cursor` (for DESC ordering, assumes monotonic IDs)\n- Response: `{ items: [...], nextCursor: string | null }` — `nextCursor` is null if page didn't fill (no more data)\n\n### 4. Database Query Pattern\n\nAll queries use **raw parameterized SQL** via template literals:\n\n```typescript\nconst rows = await db.rawSql<RowType[]>`\n  SELECT col1, col2\n  FROM table\n  WHERE user_id = ${userId}\n    AND status = ${status}\n  ORDER BY created_at DESC\n  LIMIT ${limit}\n`;\n```\n\n**Key conventions from the codebase:**\n- Generic type param: `db.rawSql<RowType[]>` — specifies return type\n- Template literals with `${}` placeholders — parameterized to prevent SQL injection\n- Column names in snake_case (database convention)\n- Timestamps returned as `Date` objects (auto-parsed)\n- Numeric columns (id, balance, count) returned as strings, then coerced with `Number()`\n- JSON columns (metadata) returned as `Record<string, unknown>`\n- JOIN queries common for enriched data (e.g., challenge_assignments JOIN challenges)\n\n**From challenges.ts — complex query example:**\n```typescript\nasync function getAssignmentsForPeriod(db: Db, userId: string, periodKey: string) {\n  return db.rawSql<AssignmentRow[]>`\n    SELECT\n      ca.id,\n      ca.challenge_id,\n      ca.period_key,\n      ca.status,\n      ca.progress,\n      ca.target,\n      ca.expires_at,\n      ca.completed_at,\n      c.title,\n      c.description,\n      c.reward_type,\n      c.reward_amount,\n      camp.campaign_type\n    FROM challenge_assignments ca\n    JOIN challenges c ON c.id = ca.challenge_id\n    JOIN campaigns camp ON camp.id = c.campaign_id\n    WHERE ca.user_id = ${userId}\n      AND ca.period_key = ${periodKey}\n    ORDER BY c.sort_order ASC\n  `;\n}\n```\n\n### 5. Type Patterns\n\nEach route file defines its DB dependency interface and row types:\n\n```typescript\nexport interface ChallengeRoutesDeps {\n  db: Db;\n}\n\ninterface AssignmentRow {\n  id: string;\n  challenge_id: string;\n  status: string;\n  progress: number;\n  target: number;\n  expires_at: string | null;\n  completed_at: string | null;\n  title: string;\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\n**Response formatting pattern:**\nConvert DB row types to camelCase for JSON response:\n```typescript\nconst formatChallenge = (a: AssignmentRow) => ({\n  id: Number(a.id),\n  title: a.title,\n  progress: a.progress,\n  status: a.status as \"active\" | \"completed\" | \"expired\",\n  completedAt: a.completed_at ?? null,\n});\n```\n\n### 6. Error Handling\n\nConsistent pattern across routes:\n```typescript\ntry {\n  // Query logic\n} catch (err) {\n  logger.error(\"context message\", {\n    userId,\n    error: err instanceof Error ? err.message : String(err),\n  });\n  return c.json({ error: \"User-friendly message\" }, 500);\n}\n```\n\n### 7. Route Registration Flow (from index.ts)\n\n1. **Middleware applied first** (JWT auth, rate limiting) at path prefix\n2. **Route factory called with deps** (db, config, etc.)\n3. **Route mounted** via `app.route()`\n\nExample:\n```typescript\n// 1. Apply JWT auth middleware\napp.use(\n  \"/challenges/*\",\n  createJwtAuthMiddleware({ jwtSecret: config.jwtSecret, requireAllMethods: true }),\n);\n\n// 2. Mount routes\napp.route(\"/challenges\", createChallengeRoutes({ db }));\n```\n\n---\n\n## For Your `/mine/history` Implementation\n\nBased on these patterns, your new challenges history endpoint should:\n\n1. **Inherit JWT auth** — add middleware to `/challenges/*` (already in place)\n2. **Use cursor pagination** — query from `challenge_assignments` with `cursor` and `limit` params\n3. **Return consistent shape** — `{ items: [...], nextCursor: string | null }`\n4. **Add to challenges.ts** as a new route: `app.get(\"/mine/history\", async (c) => {...})`\n5. **Type the row result** and format to camelCase for response\n6. **Handle userId extraction and auth checks** at route start\n\nThe existing `/mine` endpoint in challenges.ts is already there — you just need to add `/mine/history` as a sibling route in the same factory function."}],"totalDurationMs":20088,"totalTokens":44898,"totalToolUseCount":3,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":16145,"cache_read_input_tokens":26878,"output_tokens":1868,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":16145},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
